dbt-ls [SELECTOR]

Run "dbt ls" with an interactive fzf picker over the resulting model
names, then offer the opportunity to edit the selector and retry.

Searches upward from the current directory for a dbt_project.yml file
(skipping dbt_packages/ and dbt_internal_packages/). The profiles
directory is assumed to be ./profile/ relative to that root, and the
profile name is read from the first top-level key in profiles.yml.

WORKFLOW
  1. If a selector was not supplied as an argument, or after the fzf
     picker exits without a selection, you are prompted to enter or
     edit the dbt node-selector expression.

     The model list shown in the picker is read from a per-project
     nodes cache (~/.cache/rlm-dbt/<key>/nodes.json), which is built
     once and never expires on its own. To force a re-read of the
     models after adding/renaming/removing one, pick the
     "--- REFRESH NODES CACHE (cached X ago) ---" entry at the top of
     the picker: it rebuilds the cache via `dbt ls` and reopens the
     picker with the fresh list. (Same cache and refresh entry used by
     rlm-dbt-run / rlm-dbt-build / rlm-dbt-test.)
  2. "dbt ls -s <selector> --profiles-dir <dir> --profile local_dev"
     is run via "poetry run dbt ls …".
  3. The resulting model names are shown in an fzf multi-select picker.
     TAB selects multiple entries; Enter confirms the selection.
     Ctrl-Y copies the currently marked entries (or the highlighted
     line if none are marked) to the system clipboard without exiting
     the picker; the header briefly changes to confirm the copy.
     The preview pane (rendered by ~/bin/dbt-model-preview) shows:
       name, unique_id, resource_type, package, materialized, tags,
       meta, description, upstream_count, upstream (first 8 unique
       parent node names), bq_relation (project:dataset.table —
       emitted as a clickable OSC 8 hyperlink to the GCP BigQuery
       console when fully resolved), bq_rel_source (which manifest
       supplied the relation parts), file_path (absolute),
       last_modified (mtime of the .sql file).
     The metadata is fetched once via `dbt ls --output json` for the
     selector and cached in a per-invocation temp file (cleaned up on
     exit), so the preview is instant on highlight.

     If $DBT_STATE_DIR/manifest.json exists (the same prod ref-state
     used by rlm-dbt-run / rlm-dbt-build), it is passed to
     dbt-model-preview as a fallback source. Any database / schema /
     alias fields that the local target leaves null are filled in
     from the prod manifest entry matched by unique_id, so
     bq_relation resolves to e.g. "acme-prod:dataset.table" instead
     of "?:?.alias" — common when the local profile only partially
     resolves the model.
  4. If you press ESC (or the list is empty) you are asked whether to
     edit the selector and retry, or abort.
  5. On confirmation the selected model names are printed to stdout,
     one per line, AND copied to the system clipboard
     (newline-separated). A "N model(s) copied to clipboard" message
     is printed to stderr.

SELECTOR
  Any dbt node-selection expression is accepted, e.g.:
    tag:nightly
    +my_model
    package:my_project,tag:staging

  Leave the selector blank to list all models in the project.

PREREQUISITES
  - Must be run from the project root (containing pyproject.toml).
  - poetry must be available in PATH.
  - The poetry environment must include dbt and "poetry run dbt" must
    resolve to a binary inside that venv (not a stray dbt on $PATH).
    If not, the function runs "poetry install" automatically once; if
    it is still not in the venv, the function aborts with a three-line
    diagnostic (expected venv, resolved dbt, project dir).
  - dbt_profiles.yml must exist somewhere under the current directory.

Requires: poetry, fzf, dbt (in the poetry env), jq (for the preview
pane's JSON parsing and for extracting model names from
`dbt ls --output json`).
Optional: pbcopy (macOS) / xclip / xsel for the Ctrl-Y copy binding
and the post-confirmation auto-copy; without any of these the picker
still works, but the copy features become no-ops and the header notes
that no clipboard tool was found.
